      "site.d6c3b6f90bac25f235": "Write one sentence that says what you want to understand, remember, decide, or produce after reading this guide.",
      "site.26837fdfbdc6470aba": "Write your next step.",
      "site.031857a0f03861e726": "Writing Coach",
      "site.d0cad315c201ae8f56": "Writing Coach prompts and study loop",
      "site.89e44f8c034c2425f9": "writing feedback AI",
      "site.4bfe82abf3e48160fc": "Yes. Category pages link into public guest modes, learning paths, and article clusters so learners can move from reading into tutoring, quizzes, flashcards, debate, planning, or feedback.",
      "site.c08465c7772fa7ede9": "Yes. Each category is meant to help a learner choose a guide, open the right mode, and keep studying actively.",
      "site.68900608d20d3c4265": "Yes. The guide library links into public guest modes such as Learn Anything, Socratic Instruction, Homework Coach, Math Step Coach, quizzes, flashcards, and historical conversations.",
      "site.1a3740fa59d6eb6490": "You can also start with a rough version of your real problem. A messy first prompt is fine. The session can clarify the level, audience, deadline, and style once you begin.",
      "site.f2e043b75e8b159ec8": "You can try the format in Talk to a Historical Person. If you want the wider scene before meeting a person, use Time Travel to visit a period, inspect constraints, and then ask what choices people actually had.",
      "site.c94e43c9c2d97a9af5": "You know a Socratic AI tutor worked when the learner can do three things:"
