  "blog:art-appreciation-guide-prompts-and-study-loop": {
    "sourceHash": "db51e431631e30373a3b9845201d39390f4b23ba9a26e1c557adc269caf196c4",
    "sourceStrings": {
      "site.fbd0875be91d12ed1f": "\"Ask me questions before explaining too much.\"",
      "site.2c2a82b4f1cdf0977f": "\"Check my answer before giving yours.\"",
      "site.13a031b3aabee99f2c": "\"Compare Renaissance and modern art\"",
      "site.29df60129de91e2525": "\"Explain impressionism\"",
      "site.6e260fa2bd0be72927": "\"Give me a harder version after I try.\"",
      "site.201cd90ca44b450cd9": "\"How do I look at a painting?\"",
      "site.4d7d2a10206673f8d7": "\"Keep it beginner friendly.\"",
      "site.f220c4da97503ce8a6": "\"Use examples from my exam, project, or daily life.\"",
      "site.c07cedd8f400fab1d3": "AI prompts",
      "site.0d8a7e68d401e88371": "Art Appreciation Guide prompts and study loop",
      "site.3334a6e430d61212aa": "Ask for a tiny first task.",
      "site.1bcd331b5ef9fec230": "Creativity",
      "site.c7ade179f07b420526": "End with a recap you write yourself.",
      "site.9966764746f966abe5": "For Art Appreciation Guide, a useful practice loop is:",
      "site.b884213b592537a37a": "For this mode, the job is simple: Explore artworks, styles, artists, visual choices, and what makes an image powerful.",
      "site.c077bcb35f8f76b879": "Good prompts usually include three things: the subject, your current level, and the kind of help you want. You do not need perfect wording. You only need enough context for the session to begin.",
      "site.3cb8399fd818707e38": "If the response feels too broad, narrow it. Ask for one example, one misconception, one check question, or one next step. If it feels too easy, ask for a challenge. If it feels too hard, ask for a bridge from what you already know.",
      "site.b09eea5a1f8bf16685": "Make the output more useful",
      "site.48e3f3f29813b600f1": "Prompt ideas and a repeatable study loop for getting useful learning results from Art Appreciation Guide on inspir.",
      "site.62656f47e151dcabf2": "Reading an AI response is not the same as learning. After the first answer, ask the mode to make you do something with the idea.",
      "site.0db366bee7d789e937": "Related learning paths",
      "site.34703e01be53e56487": "Request feedback on the part that felt uncertain.",
      "site.d13ed52829ac8f9ae5": "Respond before asking for the solution.",
      "site.725c328ba96c60fa28": "Start with one clear request",
      "site.7b1511f40db7799020": "State the goal in one sentence.",
      "site.1115e8dcfc987db693": "study skills",
      "site.e85f78644fc8f2af1a": "That final recap is important. When you explain the idea back, you reveal what is solid and what is still borrowed from the AI.",
      "site.7bf4a43bad030ecf01": "The best learning sessions are adjustable. This mode is tuned for art appreciation guide with its own prompts, examples, and learning flow.",
      "site.475ac58da05f1fade6": "The fastest way to get value from Art Appreciation Guide is to give the AI a learning job, not just a topic. A topic says what you are interested in. A learning job says what kind of help you need.",
      "site.eb51e27d05cde20872": "Then add a constraint that makes the session more personal:",
      "site.2e70d2b0915c157e36": "Try one of these starters:",
      "site.fda025881ab1d825c7": "Turn the mode into practice",
      "site.32feb61d4aa3606efc": "Use Art Appreciation Guide when this is the right mode for the job. If you want a related path, try Civics Coach. You can also browse the AI learning blog for study methods, Socratic learning, flashcards, roleplay, and active recall."
    }
  },
